            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ari Abramov\u2019s story began before he was born, carried in the memories of his parents who fled the Soviet Union as Jewish refugees. They landed in San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District, a neighborhood of fog, Russian bakeries, and quiet resilience. Growing up, Ari was steeped in this history\u2014a background of profound loss and fierce determination. He witnessed firsthand the silent, unaddressed trauma his parents and their friends carried, and the systemic barriers they faced. This formative experience planted the seed of his life's work.\n\nWhile his peers were drawn to tech or finance, Ari felt a pull toward service. He attended UC Santa Cruz, studying psychology, but it was a volunteer position at a youth shelter that solidified his path. There, he saw reflections of his own family\u2019s story in the eyes of displaced and struggling teens. The experience was a turning point, transforming his vague desire to \"help\" into a focused mission. He pursued his Master of Social Work at SF State, specializing in youth services.\n\nNow 27, Ari is a Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW) at a community health clinic that partners with public schools. His days are a whirlwind of crisis intervention, therapy sessions, and advocating for students navigating poverty, family dysfunction, and mental health challenges. His work is emotionally taxing, but he views it as a profound privilege.\n\nAri lives in a small but sunny apartment in the Panhandle with his partner, a public-school teacher, and one roommate. His 2.5-mile bike commute is a meditative buffer between his demanding job and his personal life, a daily ride through the city that has been his lifelong home. He knows its hills and microclimates intimately. On weekends, he de-stresses by hiking in the Marin Headlands or losing himself in the botanical gardens of Golden Gate Park.\n\nHis dream isn\u2019t one of wealth, but of impact. He aspires to one day open a small private practice focused on providing culturally competent therapy for immigrant and refugee families, bringing his own story full circle. For Ari, San Francisco isn't just a place to live; it's the landscape of his past, the theater of his present, and the foundation upon which he hopes to build a more compassionate future."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, sitting at the kitchen table in their Richmond District home. His mother stood motionless, looking out at the thick fog swallowing Geary Boulevard. Her teacup grew cold in her hands. When he asked what she was thinking about, she just turned, her eyes holding a far-off sadness, and smoothed his hair. \"Nothing, *zolotse*,\" she\u2019d said. It was the first time he understood that some wounds were invisible, and he felt a fierce, childish desire to find a way to heal them.\n\n2.\nDuring his third year at UC Santa Cruz, volunteering at a youth shelter, he met a teen who had just aged out of foster care. The boy was angry, defiant, and had built walls so high Ari felt he\u2019d never get through. One evening, they were the only two in the common room. Ari didn\u2019t push, he just sat and listened to the silence. Suddenly, the boy looked at him and said, \"Nobody ever just sits.\" It was then Ari knew his life\u2019s work wasn't to fix people, but to offer them presence.\n\n3.\nIt was the first time he successfully advocated for a student to receive comprehensive mental health and housing services, cutting through layers of bureaucracy. He remembers seeing the student\u2019s mother, a woman worn down by the system, break down in tears of pure relief in the clinic hallway. In that moment, the exhaustion of his job evaporated, replaced by a profound sense of purpose. He wasn't just a therapist; he was a fulcrum, and his effort could actually move the world for a family. This happened last year.\n\n4.\nAround age 25, his father came over to help him assemble a bookshelf in his new Panhandle apartment. After, they shared a beer. Ari tried, gently, to ask about life before America. His father looked not at him, but at the finished shelf full of Ari\u2019s psychology textbooks. \"This,\" his father said, tapping the wood, \"this is what matters. Not the old ghosts.\" Ari understood then that his father\u2019s silence was a form of protection, a fierce refusal to be defined by loss.\n\n5.\nLast spring, after a brutal week at work, his partner pulled him away for a hike in the Marin Headlands. As they stood on a ridge overlooking the Golden Gate Bridge, the city of his birth laid out below, he felt the immense weight of his clients\u2019 stories lift for a moment. He leaned his head on his partner\u2019s shoulder, the wind whipping around them. He realized this was the other side of the work: not just enduring the struggle, but actively seeking out beauty to remember what he was fighting for."
